 <img src="images/smiles/banghead.gif" alt="banghead" border="0" /></td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
No! No! No!
<br />

<br />
Let's correct a few facts.  The UN did not do it because "wow" there was no UN yet!  It was an act of the League of Nations!  According to Microsoft (cos it's too late for me to quote from something really serious)
<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">In July 1922 the League of Nations, an alliance of world powers formed in 1920 to preserve peace, issued a mandate granting control over Palestine to Britain, entrusting it to facilitate the establishment of a Jewish national home. Encouraged by British support of the Zionist cause, waves of Jewish immigrants arrived in Palestine between 1919 and 1939, each contributing to the developing Jewish community (Yishuv). </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Palestine was not a country, it was a manditated area.  It had rules etc. written down by England. The first and most important set written in 1917 (Balfour Declaration).  This was AFTER 35,000+ Jews had already settled there, starting in the late 1800's.  Way before the dates of 1919 you give.   In many ways it was a soverign nation. It even had its own governments, one for the Arabs and an assembly run by the Jewish settlers.  So as you can see, the idea of the Arabs having their own government is not within the last couple decades, but goes back to 1939.
<br />

<br />

<br />
To correct another error, England turned it over right after WWII - they had it since WWI not WWII.  
<br />

<br />
Early on, Britain did a little to keep the Jewish population down, but not as much as you claim.  And what little they did was to provent infighting with the Arabs over land.  It was not until 1939 that Britain issued a serious policy statement discouraging Jews from settling.  This is because there had been turmoil for the last 15 years between the Jews and Arabs and a full revolt in 1936-39 by the Arabs who wanted thier land back and the newly relocated Jews out.
<br />

<br />
If the British were so very against this idea of Palestine, why did they mandate it?  And yes, both England and the UN wanted to form a country out of part of Palestine. In fact, they even formed a special committee to make sure the problem would be taken care of by the time the British mandate ended in 1948.  The Arabs refused to accept the UN decision.    
<br />
From then on the situation becomes similar to that of Northern Ireland.  I once heard Bernadette Devlin speak and what she said was very revelant to this part of the world as well as her home.<span class="gensmall"></span>


