			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><div class="postbody">A very, very concise history and sources:
<br />

<br />
The Ottoman Empire ruled Jerusalem and the surrounding territory from about 1517 to 1917.  Zionism began a movement of Jews towards Jerusalem including purchasing land during this time.  This movement dates to the late 19th century...including one specific reference to 1897 ( <a href="http://www.zionist.com/zionism/series/zionism3.htm" target="_blank">http://www.zionist.com/zionism/series/zionism3.htm</a> ).  It started as a movement to establish a national homeland for Jews on historic Israel.  It was based on a tract by Theodor Herzl called "A Jewish State" proposing a national homeland as a solution to oppression and persecution against Jews worldwide.  This was during the time of Ottoman control of "Palestine."
<br />

<br />
Britain militarily occupied the "Palestine" as a consequence of the defeat of the Ottoman Empire in 1917.  The Balfour Declaration was signed in 1917 BEFORE the establishment of the British Mandate.  The Balfour Declaration can be found at this site ( <a href="http://www.yale.edu/lawweb/avalon/mideast/balfour.htm" target="_blank">http://www.yale.edu/lawweb/avalon/mideast/balfour.htm</a> ) and demonstrates British government support for Jewish Zionisht aspirations for a national homeland IN "Palestine."
<br />

<br />

<br />
In 1920, Britain was given the responsibility of administering Palestine via the British Mandate of the League of Nations and a civil administration took over from the military.  The Mandate included
<br />
1.  What is now Israel, Gaza, and the West Bank
<br />
2.  The Golan Heights, ceded to the French Protectorate of Syria in 1922.
<br />
3.  What became Trans-Jordan and is now Jordan.  "Trans-Jordan" meant across the Jordan River from the main portion of Palestine.  It was separated from "Palestine" in 1921.
<br />
The mandate called for the mandatory authority to establish a Jewish homeland in "Palestine"
<br />
( <a href="http://www.palestinefacts.org/pf_mandate_overview.php" target="_blank">http://www.palestinefacts.org/pf_mandate_overview.php</a> and <a href="http://www.palestinefacts.org/pf_ww1_british_mandate.php" target="_blank">http://www.palestinefacts.org/pf_ww1_british_mandate.php</a> )
<br />

<br />
After the conclusion of World War 2, the British sought to leave Palestine and ceded to the United Nations the responsibility of determining how to resolve Jewish v. Arab interests.  The UN established a plan for partitioning Palestine and issued UN General Assembly Resolution 181 in 1947 that created intended boundaries for Jewish and Arab states.  The plan gave the northern coastal region, Eastern Galilee (surround the Sea of Galilee), and the Negev desert to the Jewish state.  The rest was planned for the "Palestinian" (aka Arab) state.   The proportion was approximately 55% Jewish and 45% Arab.  ( <a href="http://www.wikipedia.org/wiki/Partition_of_Palestine" target="_blank">http://www.wikipedia.org/wiki/Partition_of_Palestine</a> )
<br />

<br />
The Jews accepted the plan although they had reservations regarding security.  The Arabs rejected the plan and requested other Arab states to join them in a war for political control over the entire region.  This war occurred in 1948 and resulted in what was then called the "Green Line" (and we call the "pre-1967" borders) via an armistice in 1949.  Israel gained about 50% more land and ended up with approximately 70% of the land area.  Egypt occupied Gaza and Jordan occupied the West Bank to prevent Israeli control over those territories.  I've included the wiki pages because they give a good perspective and seem relatively "balanced".
<br />

<br />
( <a href="http://www.wikipedia.org/wiki/1948_Arab-Israeli_War" target="_blank">http://www.wikipedia.org/wiki/1948_Arab-Israeli_War</a> )
<br />

<br />
The next major altercation surrounded Egyptian nationalization of the Suez Canal in 1956.  The canal was built by a joint Egyptian/French effort from 1859-1869 with the intention that it would be jointly administered for 99 years and then revert to Egyptian control.  Britain purchased the Egyptian stocks (portion) in 1875.  Britain gained by treaty the right to station military forces on the canal in 1936.  In 1954 Egypt and Britian agreed to a force reduction plan that would turn the canal over to Egypt by 1961.  In 1956 Nasser short-circuited that plan by nationalizing the canal.  France and Britain joined forces attacking Nasser and Nasser responded by sinking 40 vessels that were on the canal at that time.  France and Britain secretly conspired to have Israel also attack Egypt.  The US and the Soviet Union step in to stop the war.
<br />
( <a href="http://i-cias.com/e.o/suez_can.htm" target="_blank">http://i-cias.com/e.o/suez_can.htm</a>  and 
<br />
<a href="http://www.historyguy.com/suez_war_1956.html" target="_blank">http://www.historyguy.com/suez_war_1956.html</a> )
<br />

<br />
Fatah (al Fatah means "the victory") was founded by Yasser Arafat in 1957 in the aftermath of the war for the Suez Canal.  The group's purpose was full independence for "Palestinian" Arabs.  Fatah later joined the Palestinian Liberation Organization in 1968 in the aftermath from the 1967 Six Day War.
<br />
( <a href="http://www.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fateh" target="_blank">http://www.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fateh</a> )
<br />

<br />
The Palestinian Liberation Organization was formed in 1964 as an umbrella organization to unify and coordinate various groups opposed to Israeli control of "Palestine".   The Palestinian Liberation Army was the military wing and was established in Gaza until 1967.  The listed site suggests Arafat collaboration/leadership of the PLA.
<br />

<br />
( <a href="http://www.cyberus.ca/~baker/pal_plo_1.htm" target="_blank">http://www.cyberus.ca/~baker/pal_plo_1.htm</a> )
<br />

<br />
The Six Day War is a very intricate subject that deserves an extensive treatment.  If any one nation were to blame for the start of the war, it would probably be the Soviet Union.  They essentially passed questionable (if not intentionally false) intelligence to Egypt and Syria suggesting that Israel was about to attack.  This led to an amassing of forces by both which led Israel to strike pre-emptively.  This pre-emptive strike destroyed the majority of Egyptian and Syrian air power.  Israel then conquered Jerusalem, all of the West Bank (from Jordan), Gaza and the Sinai Desert (from Egypt).  They also pushed into and took control of the Golan Heights from Syria.  Egypt, Jordan, and Syria also received aid from Iraq, Saudi Arabia, Kuwait, Sudan, and Algeria.  At the end of the Six Day War Israeli troops were less than 100 km from the capitals of Egypt (Cairo), Syria (Damascus), and Jordan (Amman).  Egypt also closed the Suez Canal due to Israel proximity to the Canal (and in part to punish Western supporters of Israel.)  Finally, the PLO/PLA moved to Jordan after Israel conquered Gaza.
<br />
( <a href="http://i-cias.com/e.o/sixdaywr.htm" target="_blank">http://i-cias.com/e.o/sixdaywr.htm</a> )
<br />

<br />
In 1969 Yasser Arafat assumed control of the united PLO.  He made an attempt to futher unite a collection of pro-Palestinian militant organizations based in Jordan.  King Hussein (OF JORDAN) accomodated the militants at first, but as time progressed his primary political struggle became maintaining control over his own nation.  To make a long story short (read the link for more details), Hussein went to war with the PLO and kicked them out in the Black September action of 1970.  One historical note was those of us who remember the term 'fedayeen' associate it first with the PLO/militants fighting against the Husseini government forces.
<br />
( <a href="http://www.onwar.com/aced/data/bravo/blacksept1970.htm" target="_blank">http://www.onwar.com/aced/data/bravo/blacksept1970.htm</a> )
<br />

<br />

<br />
Next was the Yom Kippur/Ramadan War in 1973.  This was a surprise attack by the Arabs, led by Egypt and Syria (supported by Jordan and Iraq, financed by Saudi Arabia), to reverse the humiliation of the 1967 defeat.  Israel was caught unprepared and lost some of its occupied territory, particularly in the Sinai.  The UN brokered ceasefires with Syria and Egypt.  Egypt regained control of both sides of the Suez Cana.  Western supporters were punished by the beginning of the oil embargo by OPEC nations in 1973 following conclusion of hostilities.  Israel positioned military units to support Jordan in case of extensive military intervention by Iraq and Syria in support of the PLO.
<br />
( <a href="http://i-cias.com/e.o/yomkipwr.htm" target="_blank">http://i-cias.com/e.o/yomkipwr.htm</a> )
<br />

<br />
Israel invaded and occupied Lebanon in 1982 to pursue PLO guerillas.  The PLO eventually agreed to withdraw from Lebanon to Tunis, Tunisia.  Iran/Syria-backed Hizbullah then took up arms against Israel in an attempt to force Israel out of Syrian-"managed" Lebanon.  Israel unilaterally withdrew from Lebanon in 2000.  The link I'm providing gives some of the details and hints at the broader Civil War for Lebanon that was occuring at this time.  That war deserves separate research by informed readers.
<br />
( <a href="http://www.nmhschool.org/tthornton/hizbullah.htm" target="_blank">http://www.nmhschool.org/tthornton/hizbullah.htm</a> )
<br />

<br />
The two intifadas occurred between 1987 to 1993 and the more bloody one from 2000-the present.  Since we see the results of the second one in the news, I'm not going into details on this.
<br />
( <a href="http://www.wikipedia.org/wiki/First_Intifada" target="_blank">http://www.wikipedia.org/wiki/First_Intifada</a> and <a href="http://www.wikipedia.org/wiki/Second_Intifada" target="_blank">http://www.wikipedia.org/wiki/Second_Intifada</a> )<span class="gensmall"><br /><br />Last edited by Wolen on Tue Aug 26, 2003 10:47 pm; edited 1 time in total</span>


				</div></td>
