Has this list on it.  I saw a couple of errors in the list, I was wondering if anyone else saw any.  My errors are below the list.
<br />

<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">
<br />
On April 23, Bob read this list of overlooked facts in the current Middle East situation.  These were complied by a Christian University professor. 
<br />
1. Nationhood and Jerusalem. Israel became a nation in 1312 B.C.E., two thousand years before the rise of Islam.
<br />

<br />
2. Arab refugees in Israel began identifying themselves as a part of the Palestinian people in 1967, two decades after the establishment of the modern state of Israel.
<br />

<br />
3. Since the Jewish conquest in 1272 B.C.E., the Jews have had dominion over the land for one thousand years with a continuous presence in the land for the past 3,300 years. 
<br />

<br />
4. The only Arab dominion since the conquest in 635 C.E. lasted no more than 22 years. 
<br />

<br />
5. For over 3,300 years, Jerusalem has been the Jewish capital. Jerusalem has never been the capital of any Arab or Muslim entity. Even when the Jordanians occupied Jerusalem, they never sought to make it their capital, and Arab leaders did not come to visit.
<br />

<br />
6. Jerusalem is mentioned over 700 times in Tanach, the Jewish Holy Scriptures. Jerusalem is not mentioned in the Koran.
<br />

<br />
7. King David founded the city of Jerusalem. Mohammed never came to Jerusalem.
<br />

<br />
8. Jews pray facing Jerusalem. Muslims pray with their backs toward Jerusalem. 
<br />

<br />
9. Arab and Jewish Refugees: In 1948 the Arab refugees were encouraged to leave Israel by Arab leaders promising to purge the land of Jews. Sixty-eight percent left without ever seeing and Israeli soldier.
<br />

<br />
10. The Jewish refugees were forced to flee from Arab lands due to Arab brutality, persecution and programs.
<br />

<br />
11. The number of Arab refugees who left Israel in 1948 is estimated to be around 630,000. The number of Jewish refugees from Arab land is estimated to be the same.
<br />

<br />
12. Arab refugees were INTENTIONALLY not absorbed or integrated into the Arab lands to which they fled, despite the vast Arab territory. Out of the 100,000,000 refugees since World War II, theirs is the only refugee group in the world that has never been absorbed or integrated into their own peoples' lands. Jewish refugees were completely absorbed into Israel, a country no larger than the state of New Jersey.
<br />

<br />
13. The Arab-Israeli Conflict: The Arabs are represented by eight separate nations, not including the Palestinians. There is only one Jewish nation. The Arab nations inititated all five wars and lost. Israel defended itself each time and won.
<br />

<br />
14. The P.L.O.'s Charter still calls for the destruction of the State of Israel. Israel has given the Palestinians most of the West Bank land, autonomy under the Palestinian Authority, and has supplied them.
<br />

<br />
15. Under Jordanian rule, Jewish holy sites were desecrated and the Jews were denied access to places of worship. Under Israeli rule, all Muslim and Christian sites have been preserved and made accessible to people of all faiths.
<br />

<br />
16. The U.N. Record on Israel and the Arabs: of the 175 Security Council resolutions passed before 1990, 97 were directed against Israel.
<br />

<br />
17. Of the 690 General Assembly resolutions voted on before 1990, 429 were directed against Israel.
<br />

<br />
18. The U.N. was silent while 58 Jerusalem Synagogues were destroyed by the Jordanians.
<br />

<br />
19. The U.N. was silent while the Jordanians systematically desecrated the ancient Jewish cemetery on the Mount of Olives.
<br />

<br />
20. The U.N. was silent while the Jordanians enforced an apartheid-like policy of preventing Jews from visiting the Temple Mount and the Western Wall.
<br />
</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
The errors I saw included:
<br />

<br />
Romans imposed the Diaspora on the Jews.  They were unable to occupy Jerusalem after that time (literally driven out of Israel purely on an ethnic basis circa 68-72 AD.)  A recent archaeological find at the "Colosseum" in Rome includes an inscription dated to the 70s AD that explains that the Colosseum was built with the pillage from Jerusalem.   It seems a little much to claim that Jerusalem was the capital of Judaism after 70 AD.  I also think it presents a certain amount of historical perspective to note that the Romans, not the Arabs, expelled Jews from Jerusalem.
<br />

<br />
I'm not certain about Mohammed coming to Jerusalem.  That flies in the face of Arabic/Muslim claims that he ascended from where the "Dome on the Rock" is.  (Not that I agree he ascended, just strange that they would make the claim when he never even went there.)
<br />

<br />
The claim that the Arabs started all of the wars is blatantly not true.  The French and British were responsible for the 1956 war.  Israel attacked pre-emptively in 1967 based on Soviet Union attempts, in communications to both sides, to suggest that Israel was preparing to attack. 
<br />

<br />
Follow that logic...there is significant historical information to prove this:
<br />

<br />
1.  The Soviet Union communicated to Arab States that Israel was amassing troops.
<br />

<br />
2.  Israel denied and invited Arab State representatives to visit...not sure if they did nor not, though the amassing was supposed to be near the Golan Heights.
<br />

<br />
3.  Arab States did amass troops in response.
<br />

<br />
4.  Israel's military at the time was a working military (roughly equivalent to our reserves), so mobilizing to 'wait' at the border would have destroyed their economy.  They chose to attack in order to respond to the possibility of aggression.
<br />

<br />
In other words, the 1967 conflict probably can't be blamed on either...though it would be a little more accurate to portray Israel as the agressor...much in the same way that it is a little more accurate to portray the US as the agressor in Iraq, even though our response is actually a followup to Hussein's unwillingness to meet either the terms of the 1991 ceasefire or the UN resolutions since then.
<br />

<br />
Just curious if anyone else sees any blatantly incorrect items in that list.  (Not trying to foment a philosophical or sectarian fight, really is curiosity.)
<br />

<br />
Wolen<span class="gensmall"></span>


